{"title_page": "Camano Island", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{distinguish|Kamano Island|Camino Island}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Camano Island\n|settlement_type          = [[Census-designated place|CDP]]\n|nickname                 =\n|motto                    =\n|image_skyline            = Cama Beach Resort 12.jpg\n|imagesize                =\n|image_caption            = The island's western beach at [[Cama Beach State Park]]\n|image_map = Island County Washington Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Camano Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location within Island County and Washington\n|image_map1               =\n|mapsize1                 =\n|map_caption1             =\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Washington|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Island County, Washington|Island]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[Waterbody]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[Puget Sound]]\n|government_type          =\n|leader_title             =  \n|leader_name              =\n|leader_title1            =\n|leader_name1             =\n|established_title        =\n|established_date         =\n|unit_pref  =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_magnitude           =\n|area_total_km2           = 245.9\n|area_land_km2            = 103.0\n|area_water_km2           = 142.9\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 94.9\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 39.8\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 55.2\n|length_mi                = 15.6\n|width_km                 = 1.21\u201310.62\n|width_mi                 = 0.75\u20136.6\n|dimensions_footnotes     = \n|elevation_ft             = 52\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_total         = 15661\n|population_density_km2   = 129.6\n|population_density_sq_mi = 335.6\n|population_est           = \n|pop_est_as_of            = \n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific (PST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -8\n|timezone_DST             = PDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -7\n|coordinates              = <!--{{coord|48|11|37|N|122|29|11|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}-->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 98282\n|area_code                =\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 53-09365\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1503722<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite gnis|id=1503722|name=Camano}}</ref>\n|blank2_name              = \n|blank2_info              = \n|website                  =\n|footnotes                =\n}}\n\n'''Camano Island''' {{IPAc-en|k|\u0259|\u02c8|m|e\u026a|n|o\u028a}} is a large [[island]] in [[Possession Sound]], a section of [[Puget Sound]]. It is part of [[Island County, Washington]], and is located between [[Whidbey Island]] and the mainland ([[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]) by the [[Saratoga Passage]] to the west and [[Port Susan]] and Davis Slough to the east. The island has one road connection to the mainland, via [[Washington State Route 532|State Route 532]] over the [[Camano Gateway Bridge]] at the northeast end of the island, connecting to the city of [[Stanwood, Washington|Stanwood]].\n\nThe island has a total area of {{convert|39.77|sqmi|sqkm}}, making it one of the largest in the state of Washington. It has a year-round population of 15,661 as of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The population peaks at over 17,000 during the summer months due to the presence of \"[[snowbird (people)|snowbirds]]\" and other part-time residents with vacation homes on the island. It is an [[unincorporated area]] with several small communities and shares civic facilities with nearby Stanwood, including its [[school district]], [[post office]], and emergency services.\n\nCamano Island is home to two state parks, [[Cama Beach State Park|Cama Beach]] and [[Camano Island State Park]], and several county and local parks.\n\n==History==\n\n===Etymology===\n\nCamano Island was named in 1790 for the [[Spain|Spanish]] explorer [[Jacinto Caama\u00f1o]] by compatriot [[Francisco de Eliza]], who mapped [[Admiralty Inlet]].<ref name=\"Meany\">{{cite book |last=Meany |first=Edmond S. |authorlink=Edmond S. Meany |year=1923 |title=Origin of Washington Geographic Names |page=33 |publisher=University of Washington Press |oclc=1963675 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001444300 |via=[[HathiTrust]] |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The original name of the island was ''Kal-lut-chin'' which in the language of the indigenous [[Snohomish (tribe)|Snohomish]] tribe means \"land jutting into a bay\".<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=7}}</ref><ref name=wasp>{{cite web |url=http://parks.state.wa.us/484/Camano-Island |title=Camano Island State Park |publisher=Washington State Parks |accessdate=February 21, 2016}}</ref> They used the island as a base during the [[fishing]] and [[shellfish]] gathering expeditions.<ref name=\"wildlife\"/> [[Charles Wilkes]], during the [[United States Exploring Expedition|Wilkes Expedition]] of 1838\u20131842, named it ''MacDonough Island'' in honor of [[Thomas MacDonough]] for his victory of the [[Battle of Plattsburgh|Battle of Lake Champlain]] during the [[War of 1812]]. Following this theme, Wilkes named the body of water between Camano and Whidbey Island after MacDonough's flagship the ''[[USS Saratoga (1814)|Saratoga]]''. When [[Henry Kellett]] reorganized the official British Admiralty charts in 1847, he removed Wilkes' name ''MacDonough'' and bestowed the name ''Camano'', which the Spanish had originally given to [[Admiralty Inlet]] in 1790. Wilkes' name ''Saratoga Passage'' was retained.<ref>{{cite book |year=1971 |last=Phillips |first=James W. |title=Washington State Place Names |publisher=University of Washington Press |isbn=0-295-95158-3}}</ref>\n\nJacinto Caama\u00f1o explored much of the [[Pacific Northwest]] going as far north as what is now [[Alaska]] for the Spanish. He began his expedition far to the south in [[San Blas, Nayarit|San Blas]], [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"cofc\">{{cite web | url = http://camanoisland.org/about-camano/area-history/ | title = Area History | publisher = Camano Island Chamber of Commerce | accessdate = April 13, 2015}}</ref> In addition to its Snohomish name the island has also been known as ''Macdonough Island'' named for [[Thomas Macdonough]] a [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] officer during the [[War of 1812]] and as Perry Island after an 1855 treaty between local Native Americans and [[Washington Territory]] governor [[Isaac Stevens]].<ref name=\"cofc\"/> The first Euro-American settlers on the island arrived at the time of the signing of the treaty.<ref name=wasp/> The island was also called ''Crow Island'' during the early 20th century.<ref name=\"cofc\"/> The modern translation of Camano into the [[Lushootseed]] language, used by Coast Salish tribes, is {{lang|lut|\u0294\u0259w\u0313alus}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=sda\u0294da\u0294 g\u02b7\u0259\u026c dib\u0259\u026c dx\u02b7l\u0259\u0161ucid \u0294aci\u026ctalbix\u02b7 \u2014 Puget Sound Geographical names |url=https://tulaliplushootseed.com/places/ |publisher=Tulalip Tribes of Washington |accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n\nThe island was shared between several local Coast Salish groups, who settled along beaches and gathered [[shellfish]], hunted game, and cultivated berries. Among the groups were the [[Kikiallus Indian Nation|Kikiallus]], [[Lower Skagit]], [[Sauk-Suiattle]], [[Snohomish people|Snohomish]], and [[Stillaguamish people|Stillaguamish]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hollenbeck |first1=Jan L. |last2=Moss |first2=Madonna |year=1987 |title=A Cultural Resource Overview: Prehistory, Ethnography and History: Mt. Baker-Snoqualmie National Forest |publisher=[[United States Forest Service]] |page=151 |oclc=892024380 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/005998596 |via=[[HathiTrust]] |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kimball |first1=Arthur |last2=Dean |first2=John |year=1994 |title=Camano Island: Life and Times in Island Paradise |page=5 |publisher=Stanwood/Camano News Printing |oclc=33143673 |ref=harv}}</ref> In 2005, archaeologists at [[Cama Beach State Park|Cama Beach]] on the southwest coast of the island uncovered Salish artifacts and human remains that were dated to 1,600 years [[before present]]; the site is believed to have been a seasonal or permanent village and burial ground.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Lynn |date=June 12, 2008 |title=Newest state park: beach, cabins, conflict |page=A1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2004472164_statepark12m.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> A major landslide on the south side of Camano Island in the 1820s reduced the size of the island and caused a [[tsunami]] on Saratoga Passage.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=January 6, 2015 |title='The Tsunami House': Camano Island home built to withstand disaster |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/the-tsunami-house-camano-island-home-built-to-withstand-disaster/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Shipman |first=Hugh |date=December 2001 |title=The Fall of Camano Head: A Snohomish Account of a Large Landslide and Tsunami in Possession Sound During the Early 1800s |pages=13\u201314 |journal=TsuInfo Alert |volume=3 |issue=6 |url=https://www.dnr.wa.gov/Publications/ger_tsuinfo_2001_v3_no6.pdf |publisher=[[Washington State Department of Natural Resources]] |accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy the early 19th century, during the beginning of relations between Coast Salish tribes and white explorers, the island was divided between the Kikiallus in the north, with six permanent villages, and seasonal villages for the Snohomish in the south.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=8}}</ref> White settlement on the island began in the 1850s and it was included in the newly-established [[Island County, Washington|Island County]] in 1853. The first major settlement on the island was at Ustalady (originally spelled Ustaladdy), which would be home to several sawmills.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=11}}</ref><ref name=\"Times-1959\">{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Lucile |authorlink=Lucile Saunders McDonald |date=May 10, 1959 |title=Camano Island: Area of Summer Resorts |pages=2\u20133 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The first sawmill on the island was constructed by Thomas Cranney in 1858 and a [[school district]] was organized in 1862 to serve 17 students in a one-room [[One-room schools|schoolhouse]].<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=12\u201316}}</ref>\n\nCranney's sawmill at Ustalady was seized by the federal government in 1876 due to his bankruptcy and sold the following year to the [[Puget Mill Company]], which enlarged it to handle 75,000 [[board feet]] per day.<ref name=\"KD-19\">{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=19\u201320}}</ref> A [[plat]] for Ustalady was filed in 1891, with the town boasting three stores, two hotels, a [[telegraph]] line, and daily [[steamship]] service to [[Coupeville, Washington|Coupeville]].<ref name=\"KD-19\"/> The area had a large population of [[Chinese American|Chinese]] and [[Norwegian American|Norwegian]] immigrants who worked at the mill until the former were expelled by [[Anti-Chinese violence in Washington|anti-Chinese riots]] in the 1880s.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=31}}</ref> By the [[1880 United States Census|1880 census]], there were 112 residents in Ustalady and 74 Coast Salish peoples in other settlements on Camano Islande.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=37}}</ref> Following the [[Panic of 1893]], the Ustalady sawmill was closed and left 125 residents unemployed,<ref name=\"KD-19\"/> but five [[wood shingle|shingle]] mills were later opened to capitalize on the island's timber.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Prasse |first1=Karen |author2=Stanwood Area Historical Society |year=2006 |title=Camano Island |pages=46\u201349 |series=Images of America |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |isbn=0-7385-3135-9 |oclc=71248462 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kde9KJ4PSEUC |via=Google Books |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n\nCamano Island was identified as an ideal location for farming and [[vacation home]]s during the early 20th century, as logging had cleared the island's old-growth forests.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=47}}</ref> A [[cable ferry]] connecting the island's north end to [[Stanwood, Washington|Stanwood]] was replaced by a bridge in 1909.<ref>{{cite book |last=Essex |first=Alice |year=1971 |title=The Stanwood Story, Volume I |pages=51\u201356 |publisher=[[Stanwood Camano News]] |oclc=36113496 |ref=harv}}</ref> The first [[resort town|resort settlements]] on Camano Island at Ustalady, Juniper Beach, and Madrona beach were established in the 1920s, but were later dwarfed by larger resorts like Cama Beach (opened in 1936).<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=57\u201360}}</ref> During the [[Prohibition]] era, Camano Island was used as a major transiting point for [[rumrunner]]s due to its remoteness and proximity to Canadian waters.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=63\u201364}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cameron |first1=David A. |last2=LeWarne |first2=Charles P. |last3=May |first3=M. Allan |last4=O'Donnell |first4=Jack C. |last5=O'Donnell |first5=Lawrence E. |year=2005 |title=Snohomish County: An Illustrated History |page=215 |publisher=Kelcema Books LLC |location=Index, Washington |isbn=978-0-9766700-0-1 |oclc=62728798}}</ref> The Juniper Beach area was also home to a new [[oyster farm ]]that was established in 1930 and helped sustain the island during the [[Great Depression]].<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=65\u201366}}</ref>\n\nIn 1943, the Puget Mill Company began developing its plots into residential subdivisions, ushering in the arrival of permanent summer homes on the island.<ref name=\"Times-1959\"/> The Stillaguamish River bridge to Stanwood was replaced in July 1950 by the [[Mark Clark Bridge]] and the island's roads were also improvedb by the state government.<ref name=\"KD-75\">{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=75\u201376}}</ref> A [[Camano Island State Park|new state park]] was established in 1948 and opened the following year after a day-long event in which 800 residents cleared the land to prepare for park development.<ref name=\"KD-75\"/> In the 1950s, the island received its own [[post office]], having previously been part of the Stanwood post office's delivery area, an organized [[fire department]], and [[telephone]] service.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=79\u201380}}</ref> Major population growth in the 1960s and early 1970s caused strain on the island's infrastructure, requiring the creation of a new [[urban planning|planning office]] and a satellite [[county courthouse]].<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=91\u201394}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\nCamano Island is located within the [[Puget Sound]], separated from the mainland of [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] by [[Port Susan]] and Union Slough. It lies east of the [[Saratoga Passage]], which separates it from the larger [[Whidbey Island]], and is south of [[Skagit Bay]].<ref>{{cite report |date=March 2012 |title=Island County Shoreline Master Program Update: Shoreline Inventory and Characterization |chapter=Chapter 6: East Whidbey/Camano Island Shorelines |pages=1, 44, 58 |publisher=Island County |chapterurl=https://www.islandcountywa.gov/Planning/LandUseDocuments/Ch.%206%20East%20Whidbey%20Camano%20Island.pdf |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The northern entrance to Camano Island is located {{convert|55|mi|km}} north of [[Seattle]]. The island itself is {{convert|15.6|mi|km}} long and has a width of {{convert|0.75 to 6.6|mi|km}},{{cn|date=February 2020}} with {{convert|52|mi|km}} of shoreline.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stripling |first=Sherry |date=March 27, 2005 |title=Island Life: Camano's shifting sands |page=K6 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/island-life-camanos-shifting-sands/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the Camano CDP has a total area of 94.9&nbsp;square miles (245.9&nbsp;km\u00b2), of which, 39.8&nbsp;square miles (103.0&nbsp;km\u00b2) of it is land and 55.2&nbsp;square miles (142.9&nbsp;km\u00b2) of it (58.11%) is water.{{cn|date=February 2020}} Approximately 83 percent of the shoreline around the island is privately owned.<ref name=\"Herald-Barnum\">{{cite news |last=Sanders |first=Julia-Grace |date=September 9, 2019 |title=Camano Island's newest park offers expanded waterfront access |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/camano-islands-newest-park-offers-expanded-waterfront-access/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe island has a wide array of native and migratory birds, including [[bald eagle]]s and [[heron]]s.<ref name=\"Times-Barnum\">{{cite news |last=Doughton |first=Sandi |authorlink=Sandi Doughton |date=August 27, 2016 |title=Nature lovers scramble to save wild beach on Camano Island |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/nature-lovers-scramble-to-save-wild-beach-on-camano-island/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Last glacial period|Last Ice Age]] the island, sound and land surrounding the sound was covered by a mile thick sheet of ice. As temperatures rose the glacier receded, carving the island and leaving behind deposits of [[glacial till]].<ref name=\"wildlife\">{{cite web | url = http://www.parks.wa.gov/parks/?selectedpark=Camano%20Island&subject=wildlife | title = Camano Island State Park: Wildlife and Environmental Features | accessdate = August 19, 2014 | publisher = Washington State Parks |archive-date=March 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100319213623/http://www.parks.wa.gov/parks/?selectedpark=Camano%20Island&subject=wildlife}}</ref>\n\n===Communities===\n\n*[[Utsalady, Washington|Utsalady]]\n*Terry's Corner (including new town center)\n*Madrona Beach\n*Sunset Beach\n*Juniper Beach\n*Lona Beach\n*Roackaway Beach\n*Maple Grove Beach\n\n===Parks and recreation===\n\nThe [[Washington State Parks|state parks system]] has two facilities on Camano Island: [[Camano Island State Park]] and [[Cama Beach State Park]], both located on the west side of the island. Camano Island State Park, near Elger Bay, was opened in 1949 after a one-day volunteer effort with 500 local residents to prepare the property.<ref>{{cite web |last=Prasse |first=Karen |date=July 5, 2008 |title=Stanwood and Camano Island residents build a park in one day on July 27, 1949. |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/8601 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> It has {{convert|6,700|ft|m}} of shoreline, camping areas, and hiking trails on {{convert|244|acre|ha}} of land.<ref>{{cite web |title=Camano Island State Park |url=https://parks.state.wa.us/484/Camano-Island |publisher=Washington State Parks |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Cama Beach State Park opened in 2008 at the site of a former beach resort, which was restored with beachside cabins and hiking trails.<ref>{{cite news |last=True |first=Kathryn |date=June 12, 2008 |title=Launching a new era at Cama Beach State Park |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/outdoors/launching-a-new-era-at-cama-beach-state-park/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCamano Island also has 13 local parks maintained by the Island County government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Island County Parks: Camano Island |url=https://www.islandcountywa.gov/PublicWorks/Parks/Pages/camano-island-parks.aspx |publisher=Island County Parks |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The largest park, Camano Ridge, includes {{convert|400|acre|ha}} of inland protected forestland and hiking trails that were transferred from the [[Washington State Department of Natural Resources]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jennings |first=Mary |date=June 4, 2019 |title=Local residents seek name change for Camano Ridge Park |url=https://www.goskagit.com/scnews/news/local-residents-seek-name-change-for-camano-ridge-park/article_302c2058-8641-11e9-b99b-bff808b0de85.html |work=Stanwood Camano News |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> At the north end of the island is Iverson Preserve, a {{convert|120|acre|ha}} beach and [[estuary]] with fishing and boat access.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=January 6, 2016 |title=Meeting planned on future of Iverson Preserve park on Camano |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/meeting-planned-on-future-of-iverson-preserve-park-on-camano/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Barnum Point County Park on Port Susan was opened in August 2019 with {{convert|167|acre|ha}} of waterfront space, acquired with $750,000 in private donations through a local [[land trust]].<ref name=\"Herald-Barnum\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n| title = Estimated population\n| percentages = pagr\n| 1860 | 58\n| 1870 | 157\n| 1880 | 186\n| 1895 | 200\n| 1900 | 460\n| 1910 | 678\n| 1920 | 910\n| 1930 | 679\n| 1940 | 876\n| 1950 | 1,160\n| 1960 | 1,395\n| 1970 | 2,600\n| 1980 | 5,080\n| 1990 | 7,329\n| 2000 | 13,347\n| 2010 | 15,661\n| 2017 | 15,989\n| source = Kimball & Dean (1994)<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=126}}</ref><br />United States Census Bureau<ref>{{cite web |title=Community Facts: Camano CDP, Washington |url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/cf/1.0/en/place/Camano%20CDP,%20Washington/ALL |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=September 26, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\nCamano Island has a large seasonal population of [[Snowbird (person)|snowbirds]] and other part-time residents, which brings the summer population of the island to an estimated 17,000.{{cn|date=February 2020}} The retiree population on the island began arriving in the mid-20th century, including residents from outside of Washington state.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scott Freeburn |first=Nancy |date=June 2, 1963 |title=Camano\u2014Where the Old Grow Young |pages=10\u201311 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> Based on [[Washington locations by per capita income|per capita income]], one of the more reliable measures of affluence, Camano ranks 99th of 522 areas in the state of Washington to be ranked.\n\n===2000 census===\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]], there were 13,347 people, 5,357 households, and 4,028 families residing in the Camano Island CDP. The [[population density]] was 335.6 people per square mile (129.6/km\u00b2). There were 6,709 housing units at an average density of 168.7/sq&nbsp;mi (65.1/km\u00b2). The [[Race (United States Census)|racial makeup]] of the CDP was 95.6% White, 0.3% African American, 0.8% Native American, 0.7% Asian, 0.3% Pacific Islander, 0.6% from other races, and 1.8% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.1% of the population.<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=September 11, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThere were 5,357 households out of which 28.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 66.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 6.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 24.8% were non-families. 20.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.49 and the average family size was 2.86.<ref name=\"GR2\"/>\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 24.1% under the age of 18, 4.8% from 18 to 24, 25.2% from 25 to 44, 27.7% from 45 to 64, and 18.3% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 99.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 96.9 males.<ref name=\"GR2\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $54,262, and the median income for a family was $60,013. Males had a median income of $47,309 versus $31,250 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $24,362. About 4.4% of families and 5.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 6.5% of those under age 18 and 3.3% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"GR2\"/>\n\n==Government==\n\nCamano Island is part of [[Island County, Washington|Island County]], despite its only road connection leading to [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]], and has no incorporated communities. The island's residents have previously proposed [[Municipal incorporation|incorporating]] as a city or joining Snohomish County to increase access to services, but to no result.<ref>{{cite news |last=Caldwell |first=Evan |date=November 16, 2017 |title=Camano's route to clout may be the tiny, historic Port of Mabana |url=https://www.goskagit.com/scnews/news/camano-s-route-to-clout-may-be-the-tiny-historic/article_ebbd9083-5999-50d9-bc79-6b04b08934da.html |work=Stanwood Camano News |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Island County maintains a small [[civic center|government campus]] on Camano Island that opened in the 1970s to house the county sheriff and other offices.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=July 16, 2018 |title=New government building being designed for Camano Island |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-government-building-being-designed-for-camano-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The campus is planned to be replaced by the new Island County Administration Building, which is set to open in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wendel |first=Peggy |date=July 30, 2019 |title=Camano to break ground on new county admin building |url=https://www.goskagit.com/scnews/news/camano-to-break-ground-on-new-county-admin-building/article_29451810-b21c-11e9-a381-8b45e98ad632.html |work=Stanwood Camano News |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe island shares several of its services with neighboring Stanwood, including the [[Stanwood-Camano School District]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=May 23, 2018 |title=Work begins on new Stanwood high school |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/work-begins-on-new-stanwood-high-school/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The school district has two [[elementary school]]s on Camano Island, opened in the 2000s, while older students attend classes at Stanwood's schools.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slager |first=Melissa |date=November 6, 2005 |title=Stanwood schools ponder tax |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/stanwood-schools-ponder-tax/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> [[Sno-Isle Libraries]], which serves Island and Snohomish counties, opened a [[public library]] inside a temporary space on Camano Island as part of a pilot program that began in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pesznecker |first=Scott |date=May 29, 2008 |title=Camano Island library a hit in first year |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/camano-island-library-a-hit-in-first-year/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> A permanent library at Terry's Corner opened in August 2015 after voters on the island approved a $2.3 million bond measure to remodel a former restaurant.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=June 6, 2015 |title=New Camano library set to open this summer |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-camano-library-set-to-open-this-summer/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Events===\n* The Port Susan Snow Goose & Birding Festival (February)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowgoosefest.org/|title=Port Susan Snow Goose & Birding Festival|work=Snowgoosefest|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* The Camano Island Mother's Day Art Studio Tour (May)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.camanoarts.org|title=The Camano Island Mother's Day Art Studio Tour|work=Camanoarts.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* The Spring Art Show (June)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stanwoodcamanoarts.com|title=The Spring Art Show|publisher=Stanwoodcamanoarts.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* Art by the Bay, The Stanwood\u2013Camano Festival of Art and Music (July)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artbythebay.org|title=Art by the Bay|work=Artbythebay.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* The Stanwood Camano Community Fair (August) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stanwoodcamanofair.org|title=Stanwood-Camano Community Fair|work=Stanwoodcamanofair.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* The Harvest Jubilee (September)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://harvestjubilee.org|title=Harvest Jubilee|work=Harvestjubilee.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Notable people===\n\n* [[Mark W. Clark]], U.S. Army general<ref>{{cite news |date=June 7, 1950 |title=Gen. Mark Clark 'Might' Run For Senate, Say Republicans |page=19 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n* [[William Corson]], actor\n* [[Colton Harris-Moore]], former fugitive known as the \"Barefoot Bandit\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Lacitis |first=Erik |date=December 14, 2011 |title=Dark portrait emerges of Barefoot Bandit's life |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/dark-portrait-emerges-of-barefoot-bandits-life/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Margaret Haugen]], state senator<ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=November 28, 2012 |title=Sen. Mary Margaret Haugen was a major voice for county transit |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/sen-mary-margaret-haugen-was-a-major-voice-for-county-transit/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Dave Hayes (politician)|Dave Hayes]], state legislator<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Sullivan |first=Joseph |date=September 4, 2018 |title=Beyond Seattle, legislative candidates try to woo voters with plans to ease housing costs |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/its-not-just-a-seattle-thing-candidates-for-legislature-try-to-woo-voters-with-plans-to-ease-housing-costs/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Caitlin Kinnunen]], actress<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=June 6, 2019 |title=Local theater helped propel Camano Island native to stardom |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/local-theater-helped-propel-camano-island-native-to-stardom/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas T. Minor]], former mayor of Seattle and Port Townsend<ref>{{cite news |last=Patrick |first=Linnea |date=November 19, 2017 |title=Back When: The life and death of Dr. Minor |url=https://www.peninsuladailynews.com/life/back-when-the-life-and-death-of-dr-minor/ |work=[[Peninsula Daily News]] |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Neale (pilot)|Robert Neale]], ace pilot<ref>{{cite news |last=Barber |first=Mike |date=May 25, 2001 |title=Before the U.S. entered WWII, the Flying Tigers were already in the fight |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/Before-the-U-S-entered-WWII-the-Flying-Tigers-1055750.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Laurie Z]], musician\n* [[Alfred Zeisler]], film producer, director, actor and screenwriter\n\n==Transportation==\n\nCamano Island is connected to mainland Washington by [[Washington State Route 532|State Route 532]], which travels from the north end of the island to [[Stanwood, Washington|Stanwood]] via two bridges over the Davis Slough and [[Stillaguamish River]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=August 12, 2010 |title=Drivers, your bridge to Camano Island awaits |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/drivers-your-bridge-to-camano-island-awaits/ |work=[[The Everett Herald]] |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref> The island has several connecting roads that travel along the west and east edges to various neighborhoods and the two state parks.<ref>{{cite news |last=McQuaide |first=Mike |date=February 2, 2011 |title=A driving tour of Camano Island: laid-back vibe, no ferry ride |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/outdoors/2014107509_nwwcamano03.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref> [[Island Transit (Washington)|Island Transit]] operates free bus services connecting Camano Island to Stanwood, with onward connections to [[Mount Vernon, Washington|Mount Vernon]], [[Amtrak Cascades|Amtrak ''Cascades'']], and Everett.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 30, 2018 |title=Island Transit votes to keep its free rides |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/northwest/island-transit-votes-to-keep-its-free-rides/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral proposals for alternate ferry connections to [[Coupeville, Washington|Coupeville]] and [[Everett, Washington|Everett]] have been rejected by local residents and potential operators.<ref>{{cite news |last=Whalen |first=Nathan |date=July 18, 2008 |title=Ferry to Camano idea revived |url=http://www.whidbeynewstimes.com/news/ferry-to-camano-idea-revived/ |work=[[Whidbey News-Times]] |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Carol |date=February 2, 2019 |title=News Files: Camano said 'no' in 1999 for the third time to car ferry service |url=https://www.goskagit.com/scnews/news/news-files-camano-said-no-in-for-the-third-time/article_0343596c-2039-11e9-a202-47a322752679.html |work=Stanwood Camano News |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of islands of Washington (state)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://camanoisland.org/ Camano Island Chamber of Commerce]\n\n{{Island County, Washington}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Island County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Island County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Islands of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Islands of Puget Sound]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{distinguish|Kamano Island|Camino Island}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Camano Island\n|settlement_type          = [[Census-designated place|CDP]]\n|nickname                 =\n|motto                    =\n|image_skyline            = Cama Beach Resort 12.jpg\n|imagesize                =\n|image_caption            = The island's western beach at [[Cama Beach State Park]]\n|image_map = Island County Washington Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Camano Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location within Island County and Washington\n|image_map1               =\n|mapsize1                 =\n|map_caption1             =\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Washington|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Island County, Washington|Island]]\n|subdivision_type3        = [[Waterbody]]\n|subdivision_name3        = [[Puget Sound]]\n|government_type          =\n|leader_title             =  \n|leader_name              =\n|leader_title1            =\n|leader_name1             =\n|established_title        =\n|established_date         =\n|unit_pref  =  Imperial\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_magnitude           =\n|area_total_km2           = 245.9\n|area_land_km2            = 103.0\n|area_water_km2           = 142.9\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 94.9\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 39.8\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 55.2\n|length_mi                = 15.6\n|width_km                 = 1.21\u201310.62\n|width_mi                 = 0.75\u20136.6\n|dimensions_footnotes     = \n|elevation_ft             = 52\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_total         = 15661\n|population_density_km2   = 129.6\n|population_density_sq_mi = 335.6\n|population_est           = \n|pop_est_as_of            = \n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific (PST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -8\n|timezone_DST             = PDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -7\n|coordinates              = <!--{{coord|48|11|37|N|122|29|11|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}-->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 98282\n|area_code                =\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 53-09365\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 1503722<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite gnis|id=1503722|name=Camano}}</ref>\n|blank2_name              = \n|blank2_info              = \n|website                  =\n|footnotes                =\n}}\n\n'''Camano Island''' {{IPAc-en|k|\u0259|\u02c8|m|e\u026a|n|o\u028a}} is a large [[island]] in [[Possession Sound]], a section of [[Puget Sound]]. It is part of [[Island County, Washington]], and is located between [[Whidbey Island]] and the mainland ([[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]) by the [[Saratoga Passage]] to the west and [[Port Susan]] and Davis Slough to the east. The island has one road connection to the mainland, via [[Washington State Route 532|State Route 532]] over the [[Camano Gateway Bridge]] at the northeast end of the island, connecting to the city of [[Stanwood, Washington|Stanwood]].\n\nThe island has a total area of {{convert|39.77|sqmi|sqkm}}, making it one of the largest in the state of Washington. It has a year-round population of 15,661 as of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The population peaks at over 17,000 during the summer months due to the presence of \"[[snowbird (people)|snowbirds]]\" and other part-time residents with vacation homes on the island. It is an [[unincorporated area]] with several small communities and shares civic facilities with nearby Stanwood, including its [[school district]], [[post office]], and emergency services.\n\nCamano Island is home to two state parks, [[Cama Beach State Park|Cama Beach]] and [[Camano Island State Park]], and several county and local parks.\n\n==History==\n\n===Etymology===\n\nCamano Island was named in 1790 for the [[Spain|Spanish]] explorer [[Jacinto Caama\u00f1o]] by compatriot [[Francisco de Eliza]], who mapped [[Admiralty Inlet]].<ref name=\"Meany\">{{cite book |last=Meany |first=Edmond S. |authorlink=Edmond S. Meany |year=1923 |title=Origin of Washington Geographic Names |page=33 |publisher=University of Washington Press |oclc=1963675 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001444300 |via=[[HathiTrust]] |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The original name of the island was ''Kal-lut-chin'' which in the language of the indigenous [[Snohomish (tribe)|Snohomish]] tribe means \"land jutting into a bay\".<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=7}}</ref><ref name=wasp>{{cite web |url=http://parks.state.wa.us/484/Camano-Island |title=Camano Island State Park |publisher=Washington State Parks |accessdate=February 21, 2016}}</ref> They used the island as a base during the [[fishing]] and [[shellfish]] gathering expeditions.<ref name=\"wildlife\"/> [[Charles Wilkes]], during the [[United States Exploring Expedition|Wilkes Expedition]] of 1838\u20131842, named it ''MacDonough Island'' in honor of [[Thomas MacDonough]] for his victory of the [[Battle of Plattsburgh|Battle of Lake Champlain]] during the [[War of 1812]]. Following this theme, Wilkes named the body of water between Camano and Whidbey Island after MacDonough's flagship the ''[[USS Saratoga (1814)|Saratoga]]''. When [[Henry Kellett]] reorganized the official British Admiralty charts in 1847, he removed Wilkes' name ''MacDonough'' and bestowed the name ''Camano'', which the Spanish had originally given to [[Admiralty Inlet]] in 1790. Wilkes' name ''Saratoga Passage'' was retained.<ref>{{cite book |year=1971 |last=Phillips |first=James W. |title=Washington State Place Names |publisher=University of Washington Press |isbn=0-295-95158-3}}</ref>\n\nJacinto Caama\u00f1o explored much of the [[Pacific Northwest]] going as far north as what is now [[Alaska]] for the Spanish. He began his expedition far to the south in [[San Blas, Nayarit|San Blas]], [[Mexico]].<ref name=\"cofc\">{{cite web | url = http://camanoisland.org/about-camano/area-history/ | title = Area History | publisher = Camano Island Chamber of Commerce | accessdate = April 13, 2015}}</ref> In addition to its Snohomish name the island has also been known as ''Macdonough Island'' named for [[Thomas Macdonough]] a [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] officer during the [[War of 1812]] and as Perry Island after an 1855 treaty between local Native Americans and [[Washington Territory]] governor [[Isaac Stevens]].<ref name=\"cofc\"/> The first Euro-American settlers on the island arrived at the time of the signing of the treaty.<ref name=wasp/> The island was also called ''Crow Island'' during the early 20th century.<ref name=\"cofc\"/> The modern translation of Camano into the [[Lushootseed]] language, used by Coast Salish tribes, is {{lang|lut|\u0294\u0259w\u0313alus}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=sda\u0294da\u0294 g\u02b7\u0259\u026c dib\u0259\u026c dx\u02b7l\u0259\u0161ucid \u0294aci\u026ctalbix\u02b7 \u2014 Puget Sound Geographical names |url=https://tulaliplushootseed.com/places/ |publisher=Tulalip Tribes of Washington |accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n\nThe island was shared between several local Coast Salish groups, who settled along beaches and gathered [[shellfish]], hunted game, and cultivated berries. Among the groups were the [[Kikiallus Indian Nation|Kikiallus]], [[Lower Skagit]], [[Sauk-Suiattle]], [[Snohomish people|Snohomish]], and [[Stillaguamish people|Stillaguamish]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hollenbeck |first1=Jan L. |last2=Moss |first2=Madonna |year=1987 |title=A Cultural Resource Overview: Prehistory, Ethnography and History: Mt. Baker-Snoqualmie National Forest |publisher=[[United States Forest Service]] |page=151 |oclc=892024380 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/005998596 |via=[[HathiTrust]] |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kimball |first1=Arthur |last2=Dean |first2=John |year=1994 |title=Camano Island: Life and Times in Island Paradise |page=5 |publisher=Stanwood/Camano News Printing |oclc=33143673 |ref=harv}}</ref> In 2005, archaeologists at [[Cama Beach State Park|Cama Beach]] on the southwest coast of the island uncovered Salish artifacts and human remains that were dated to 1,600 years [[before present]]; the site is believed to have been a seasonal or permanent village and burial ground.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Lynn |date=June 12, 2008 |title=Newest state park: beach, cabins, conflict |page=A1 |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2004472164_statepark12m.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> A major landslide on the south side of Camano Island in the 1820s reduced the size of the island and caused a [[tsunami]] on Saratoga Passage.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=January 6, 2015 |title='The Tsunami House': Camano Island home built to withstand disaster |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/the-tsunami-house-camano-island-home-built-to-withstand-disaster/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Shipman |first=Hugh |date=December 2001 |title=The Fall of Camano Head: A Snohomish Account of a Large Landslide and Tsunami in Possession Sound During the Early 1800s |pages=13\u201314 |journal=TsuInfo Alert |volume=3 |issue=6 |url=https://www.dnr.wa.gov/Publications/ger_tsuinfo_2001_v3_no6.pdf |publisher=[[Washington State Department of Natural Resources]] |accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy the early 19th century, during the beginning of relations between Coast Salish tribes and white explorers, the island was divided between the Kikiallus in the north, with six permanent villages, and seasonal villages for the Snohomish in the south.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=8}}</ref> White settlement on the island began in the 1850s and it was included in the newly-established [[Island County, Washington|Island County]] in 1853. The first major settlement on the island was at Ustalady (originally spelled Ustaladdy), which would be home to several sawmills.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=11}}</ref><ref name=\"Times-1959\">{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Lucile |authorlink=Lucile Saunders McDonald |date=May 10, 1959 |title=Camano Island: Area of Summer Resorts |pages=2\u20133 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> The first sawmill on the island was constructed by Thomas Cranney in 1858 and a [[school district]] was organized in 1862 to serve 17 students in a one-room [[One-room schools|schoolhouse]].<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=12\u201316}}</ref>\n\nCranney's sawmill at Ustalady was seized by the federal government in 1876 due to his bankruptcy and sold the following year to the [[Puget Mill Company]], which enlarged it to handle 75,000 [[board feet]] per day.<ref name=\"KD-19\">{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=19\u201320}}</ref> A [[plat]] for Ustalady was filed in 1891, with the town boasting three stores, two hotels, a [[telegraph]] line, and daily [[steamship]] service to [[Coupeville, Washington|Coupeville]].<ref name=\"KD-19\"/> The area had a large population of [[Chinese American|Chinese]] and [[Norwegian American|Norwegian]] immigrants who worked at the mill until the former were expelled by [[Anti-Chinese violence in Washington|anti-Chinese riots]] in the 1880s.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=31}}</ref> By the [[1880 United States Census|1880 census]], there were 112 residents in Ustalady and 74 Coast Salish peoples in other settlements on Camano Islande.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=37}}</ref> Following the [[Panic of 1893]], the Ustalady sawmill was closed and left 125 residents unemployed,<ref name=\"KD-19\"/> but five [[wood shingle|shingle]] mills were later opened to capitalize on the island's timber.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Prasse |first1=Karen |author2=Stanwood Area Historical Society |year=2006 |title=Camano Island |pages=46\u201349 |series=Images of America |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |isbn=0-7385-3135-9 |oclc=71248462 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kde9KJ4PSEUC |via=Google Books |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n\nCamano Island was identified as an ideal location for farming and [[vacation home]]s during the early 20th century, as logging had cleared the island's old-growth forests.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=47}}</ref> A [[cable ferry]] connecting the island's north end to [[Stanwood, Washington|Stanwood]] was replaced by a bridge in 1909.<ref>{{cite book |last=Essex |first=Alice |year=1971 |title=The Stanwood Story, Volume I |pages=51\u201356 |publisher=[[Stanwood Camano News]] |oclc=36113496 |ref=harv}}</ref> The first [[resort town|resort settlements]] on Camano Island at Ustalady, Juniper Beach, and Madrona beach were established in the 1920s, but were later dwarfed by larger resorts like Cama Beach (opened in 1936).<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=57\u201360}}</ref> During the [[Prohibition]] era, Camano Island was used as a major transiting point for [[rumrunner]]s due to its remoteness and proximity to Canadian waters.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=63\u201364}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cameron |first1=David A. |last2=LeWarne |first2=Charles P. |last3=May |first3=M. Allan |last4=O'Donnell |first4=Jack C. |last5=O'Donnell |first5=Lawrence E. |year=2005 |title=Snohomish County: An Illustrated History |page=215 |publisher=Kelcema Books LLC |location=Index, Washington |isbn=978-0-9766700-0-1 |oclc=62728798}}</ref> The Juniper Beach area was also home to a new [[oyster farm]]that was established in 1930 and helped sustain the island during the [[Great Depression]].<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=65\u201366}}</ref>\n\nIn 1943, the Puget Mill Company began developing its plots into residential subdivisions, ushering in the arrival of permanent summer homes on the island.<ref name=\"Times-1959\"/> The Stillaguamish River bridge to Stanwood was replaced in July 1950 by the [[Mark Clark Bridge]] and the island's roads were also improvedb by the state government.<ref name=\"KD-75\">{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=75\u201376}}</ref> A [[Camano Island State Park|new state park]] was established in 1948 and opened the following year after a day-long event in which 800 residents cleared the land to prepare for park development.<ref name=\"KD-75\"/> In the 1950s, the island received its own [[post office]], having previously been part of the Stanwood post office's delivery area, an organized [[fire department]], and [[telephone]] service.<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=79\u201380}}</ref> Major population growth in the 1960s and early 1970s caused strain on the island's infrastructure, requiring the creation of a new [[urban planning|planning office]] and a satellite [[county courthouse]].<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|pages=91\u201394}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\nCamano Island is located within the [[Puget Sound]], separated from the mainland of [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] by [[Port Susan]] and Union Slough. It lies east of the [[Saratoga Passage]], which separates it from the larger [[Whidbey Island]], and is south of [[Skagit Bay]].<ref>{{cite report |date=March 2012 |title=Island County Shoreline Master Program Update: Shoreline Inventory and Characterization |chapter=Chapter 6: East Whidbey/Camano Island Shorelines |pages=1, 44, 58 |publisher=Island County |chapterurl=https://www.islandcountywa.gov/Planning/LandUseDocuments/Ch.%206%20East%20Whidbey%20Camano%20Island.pdf |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The northern entrance to Camano Island is located {{convert|55|mi|km}} north of [[Seattle]]. The island itself is {{convert|15.6|mi|km}} long and has a width of {{convert|0.75 to 6.6|mi|km}},{{cn|date=February 2020}} with {{convert|52|mi|km}} of shoreline.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stripling |first=Sherry |date=March 27, 2005 |title=Island Life: Camano's shifting sands |page=K6 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/travel/island-life-camanos-shifting-sands/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the Camano CDP has a total area of 94.9&nbsp;square miles (245.9&nbsp;km\u00b2), of which, 39.8&nbsp;square miles (103.0&nbsp;km\u00b2) of it is land and 55.2&nbsp;square miles (142.9&nbsp;km\u00b2) of it (58.11%) is water.{{cn|date=February 2020}} Approximately 83 percent of the shoreline around the island is privately owned.<ref name=\"Herald-Barnum\">{{cite news |last=Sanders |first=Julia-Grace |date=September 9, 2019 |title=Camano Island's newest park offers expanded waterfront access |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/camano-islands-newest-park-offers-expanded-waterfront-access/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe island has a wide array of native and migratory birds, including [[bald eagle]]s and [[heron]]s.<ref name=\"Times-Barnum\">{{cite news |last=Doughton |first=Sandi |authorlink=Sandi Doughton |date=August 27, 2016 |title=Nature lovers scramble to save wild beach on Camano Island |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/nature-lovers-scramble-to-save-wild-beach-on-camano-island/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Last glacial period|Last Ice Age]] the island, sound and land surrounding the sound was covered by a mile thick sheet of ice. As temperatures rose the glacier receded, carving the island and leaving behind deposits of [[glacial till]].<ref name=\"wildlife\">{{cite web | url = http://www.parks.wa.gov/parks/?selectedpark=Camano%20Island&subject=wildlife | title = Camano Island State Park: Wildlife and Environmental Features | accessdate = August 19, 2014 | publisher = Washington State Parks |archive-date=March 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100319213623/http://www.parks.wa.gov/parks/?selectedpark=Camano%20Island&subject=wildlife}}</ref>\n\n===Communities===\n\n*[[Utsalady, Washington|Utsalady]]\n*Terry's Corner (including new town center)\n*Madrona Beach\n*Sunset Beach\n*Juniper Beach\n*Lona Beach\n*Roackaway Beach\n*Maple Grove Beach\n\n===Parks and recreation===\n\nThe [[Washington State Parks|state parks system]] has two facilities on Camano Island: [[Camano Island State Park]] and [[Cama Beach State Park]], both located on the west side of the island. Camano Island State Park, near Elger Bay, was opened in 1949 after a one-day volunteer effort with 500 local residents to prepare the property.<ref>{{cite web |last=Prasse |first=Karen |date=July 5, 2008 |title=Stanwood and Camano Island residents build a park in one day on July 27, 1949. |url=https://www.historylink.org/File/8601 |work=HistoryLink |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> It has {{convert|6,700|ft|m}} of shoreline, camping areas, and hiking trails on {{convert|244|acre|ha}} of land.<ref>{{cite web |title=Camano Island State Park |url=https://parks.state.wa.us/484/Camano-Island |publisher=Washington State Parks |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Cama Beach State Park opened in 2008 at the site of a former beach resort, which was restored with beachside cabins and hiking trails.<ref>{{cite news |last=True |first=Kathryn |date=June 12, 2008 |title=Launching a new era at Cama Beach State Park |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/life/outdoors/launching-a-new-era-at-cama-beach-state-park/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCamano Island also has 13 local parks maintained by the Island County government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Island County Parks: Camano Island |url=https://www.islandcountywa.gov/PublicWorks/Parks/Pages/camano-island-parks.aspx |publisher=Island County Parks |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The largest park, Camano Ridge, includes {{convert|400|acre|ha}} of inland protected forestland and hiking trails that were transferred from the [[Washington State Department of Natural Resources]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jennings |first=Mary |date=June 4, 2019 |title=Local residents seek name change for Camano Ridge Park |url=https://www.goskagit.com/scnews/news/local-residents-seek-name-change-for-camano-ridge-park/article_302c2058-8641-11e9-b99b-bff808b0de85.html |work=Stanwood Camano News |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> At the north end of the island is Iverson Preserve, a {{convert|120|acre|ha}} beach and [[estuary]] with fishing and boat access.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=January 6, 2016 |title=Meeting planned on future of Iverson Preserve park on Camano |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/meeting-planned-on-future-of-iverson-preserve-park-on-camano/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Barnum Point County Park on Port Susan was opened in August 2019 with {{convert|167|acre|ha}} of waterfront space, acquired with $750,000 in private donations through a local [[land trust]].<ref name=\"Herald-Barnum\"/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n| title = Estimated population\n| percentages = pagr\n| 1860 | 58\n| 1870 | 157\n| 1880 | 186\n| 1895 | 200\n| 1900 | 460\n| 1910 | 678\n| 1920 | 910\n| 1930 | 679\n| 1940 | 876\n| 1950 | 1,160\n| 1960 | 1,395\n| 1970 | 2,600\n| 1980 | 5,080\n| 1990 | 7,329\n| 2000 | 13,347\n| 2010 | 15,661\n| 2017 | 15,989\n| source = Kimball & Dean (1994)<ref>{{harvp|Kimball|Dean|1994|page=126}}</ref><br />United States Census Bureau<ref>{{cite web |title=Community Facts: Camano CDP, Washington |url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/cf/1.0/en/place/Camano%20CDP,%20Washington/ALL |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=September 26, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\nCamano Island has a large seasonal population of [[Snowbird (person)|snowbirds]] and other part-time residents, which brings the summer population of the island to an estimated 17,000.{{cn|date=February 2020}} The retiree population on the island began arriving in the mid-20th century, including residents from outside of Washington state.<ref>{{cite news |last=Scott Freeburn |first=Nancy |date=June 2, 1963 |title=Camano\u2014Where the Old Grow Young |pages=10\u201311 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref> Based on [[Washington locations by per capita income|per capita income]], one of the more reliable measures of affluence, Camano ranks 99th of 522 areas in the state of Washington to be ranked.\n\n===2000 census===\n\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]], there were 13,347 people, 5,357 households, and 4,028 families residing in the Camano Island CDP. The [[population density]] was 335.6 people per square mile (129.6/km\u00b2). There were 6,709 housing units at an average density of 168.7/sq&nbsp;mi (65.1/km\u00b2). The [[Race (United States Census)|racial makeup]] of the CDP was 95.6% White, 0.3% African American, 0.8% Native American, 0.7% Asian, 0.3% Pacific Islander, 0.6% from other races, and 1.8% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.1% of the population.<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=September 11, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThere were 5,357 households out of which 28.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 66.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 6.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 24.8% were non-families. 20.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.49 and the average family size was 2.86.<ref name=\"GR2\"/>\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 24.1% under the age of 18, 4.8% from 18 to 24, 25.2% from 25 to 44, 27.7% from 45 to 64, and 18.3% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 99.5 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 96.9 males.<ref name=\"GR2\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $54,262, and the median income for a family was $60,013. Males had a median income of $47,309 versus $31,250 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $24,362. About 4.4% of families and 5.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 6.5% of those under age 18 and 3.3% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"GR2\"/>\n\n==Government==\n\nCamano Island is part of [[Island County, Washington|Island County]], despite its only road connection leading to [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]], and has no incorporated communities. The island's residents have previously proposed [[Municipal incorporation|incorporating]] as a city or joining Snohomish County to increase access to services, but to no result.<ref>{{cite news |last=Caldwell |first=Evan |date=November 16, 2017 |title=Camano's route to clout may be the tiny, historic Port of Mabana |url=https://www.goskagit.com/scnews/news/camano-s-route-to-clout-may-be-the-tiny-historic/article_ebbd9083-5999-50d9-bc79-6b04b08934da.html |work=Stanwood Camano News |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> Island County maintains a small [[civic center|government campus]] on Camano Island that opened in the 1970s to house the county sheriff and other offices.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=July 16, 2018 |title=New government building being designed for Camano Island |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-government-building-being-designed-for-camano-island/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The campus is planned to be replaced by the new Island County Administration Building, which is set to open in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wendel |first=Peggy |date=July 30, 2019 |title=Camano to break ground on new county admin building |url=https://www.goskagit.com/scnews/news/camano-to-break-ground-on-new-county-admin-building/article_29451810-b21c-11e9-a381-8b45e98ad632.html |work=Stanwood Camano News |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe island shares several of its services with neighboring Stanwood, including the [[Stanwood-Camano School District]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=May 23, 2018 |title=Work begins on new Stanwood high school |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/work-begins-on-new-stanwood-high-school/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> The school district has two [[elementary school]]s on Camano Island, opened in the 2000s, while older students attend classes at Stanwood's schools.<ref>{{cite news |last=Slager |first=Melissa |date=November 6, 2005 |title=Stanwood schools ponder tax |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/stanwood-schools-ponder-tax/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> [[Sno-Isle Libraries]], which serves Island and Snohomish counties, opened a [[public library]] inside a temporary space on Camano Island as part of a pilot program that began in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pesznecker |first=Scott |date=May 29, 2008 |title=Camano Island library a hit in first year |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/camano-island-library-a-hit-in-first-year/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref> A permanent library at Terry's Corner opened in August 2015 after voters on the island approved a $2.3 million bond measure to remodel a former restaurant.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bray |first=Kari |date=June 6, 2015 |title=New Camano library set to open this summer |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/new-camano-library-set-to-open-this-summer/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Events===\n* The Port Susan Snow Goose & Birding Festival (February)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snowgoosefest.org/|title=Port Susan Snow Goose & Birding Festival|work=Snowgoosefest|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* The Camano Island Mother's Day Art Studio Tour (May)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.camanoarts.org|title=The Camano Island Mother's Day Art Studio Tour|work=Camanoarts.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* The Spring Art Show (June)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stanwoodcamanoarts.com|title=The Spring Art Show|publisher=Stanwoodcamanoarts.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* Art by the Bay, The Stanwood\u2013Camano Festival of Art and Music (July)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artbythebay.org|title=Art by the Bay|work=Artbythebay.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* The Stanwood Camano Community Fair (August) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stanwoodcamanofair.org|title=Stanwood-Camano Community Fair|work=Stanwoodcamanofair.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* The Harvest Jubilee (September)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://harvestjubilee.org|title=Harvest Jubilee|work=Harvestjubilee.org|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Notable people===\n\n* [[Mark W. Clark]], U.S. Army general<ref>{{cite news |date=June 7, 1950 |title=Gen. Mark Clark 'Might' Run For Senate, Say Republicans |page=19 |work=The Seattle Times}}</ref>\n* [[William Corson]], actor\n* [[Colton Harris-Moore]], former fugitive known as the \"Barefoot Bandit\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Lacitis |first=Erik |date=December 14, 2011 |title=Dark portrait emerges of Barefoot Bandit's life |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/dark-portrait-emerges-of-barefoot-bandits-life/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Margaret Haugen]], state senator<ref>{{cite news |last=Cornfield |first=Jerry |date=November 28, 2012 |title=Sen. Mary Margaret Haugen was a major voice for county transit |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/sen-mary-margaret-haugen-was-a-major-voice-for-county-transit/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Dave Hayes (politician)|Dave Hayes]], state legislator<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Sullivan |first=Joseph |date=September 4, 2018 |title=Beyond Seattle, legislative candidates try to woo voters with plans to ease housing costs |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/its-not-just-a-seattle-thing-candidates-for-legislature-try-to-woo-voters-with-plans-to-ease-housing-costs/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Caitlin Kinnunen]], actress<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=June 6, 2019 |title=Local theater helped propel Camano Island native to stardom |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/life/local-theater-helped-propel-camano-island-native-to-stardom/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas T. Minor]], former mayor of Seattle and Port Townsend<ref>{{cite news |last=Patrick |first=Linnea |date=November 19, 2017 |title=Back When: The life and death of Dr. Minor |url=https://www.peninsuladailynews.com/life/back-when-the-life-and-death-of-dr-minor/ |work=[[Peninsula Daily News]] |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Neale (pilot)|Robert Neale]], ace pilot<ref>{{cite news |last=Barber |first=Mike |date=May 25, 2001 |title=Before the U.S. entered WWII, the Flying Tigers were already in the fight |page=A1 |url=https://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/Before-the-U-S-entered-WWII-the-Flying-Tigers-1055750.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Laurie Z]], musician\n* [[Alfred Zeisler]], film producer, director, actor and screenwriter\n\n==Transportation==\n\nCamano Island is connected to mainland Washington by [[Washington State Route 532|State Route 532]], which travels from the north end of the island to [[Stanwood, Washington|Stanwood]] via two bridges over the Davis Slough and [[Stillaguamish River]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fiege |first=Gale |date=August 12, 2010 |title=Drivers, your bridge to Camano Island awaits |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/drivers-your-bridge-to-camano-island-awaits/ |work=[[The Everett Herald]] |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref> The island has several connecting roads that travel along the west and east edges to various neighborhoods and the two state parks.<ref>{{cite news |last=McQuaide |first=Mike |date=February 2, 2011 |title=A driving tour of Camano Island: laid-back vibe, no ferry ride |url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/outdoors/2014107509_nwwcamano03.html |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref> [[Island Transit (Washington)|Island Transit]] operates free bus services connecting Camano Island to Stanwood, with onward connections to [[Mount Vernon, Washington|Mount Vernon]], [[Amtrak Cascades|Amtrak ''Cascades'']], and Everett.<ref>{{cite news |date=June 30, 2018 |title=Island Transit votes to keep its free rides |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/northwest/island-transit-votes-to-keep-its-free-rides/ |work=The Everett Herald |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral proposals for alternate ferry connections to [[Coupeville, Washington|Coupeville]] and [[Everett, Washington|Everett]] have been rejected by local residents and potential operators.<ref>{{cite news |last=Whalen |first=Nathan |date=July 18, 2008 |title=Ferry to Camano idea revived |url=http://www.whidbeynewstimes.com/news/ferry-to-camano-idea-revived/ |work=[[Whidbey News-Times]] |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Carol |date=February 2, 2019 |title=News Files: Camano said 'no' in 1999 for the third time to car ferry service |url=https://www.goskagit.com/scnews/news/news-files-camano-said-no-in-for-the-third-time/article_0343596c-2039-11e9-a202-47a322752679.html |work=Stanwood Camano News |accessdate=April 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of islands of Washington (state)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[https://camanoisland.org/ Camano Island Chamber of Commerce]\n\n{{Island County, Washington}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Island County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Island County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Islands of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Islands of Puget Sound]]\n", "name_user": "Albertfiedler", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a space to correct a typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camano_Island"}
{"title_page": "Economy of Sydney", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2012}}\n[[File:Australian Census 2011 demographic map - Inner Sydney by POA - BCP field 0115 Median total household income weekly.svg|300px|right|thumb|Median weekly household incomes by postal area in the [[Census in Australia#2011|2011 census]], red indicates high incomes, purple indicates low incomes. The [[North Shore, Sydney|North Shore]] and areas fronting [[Sydney Harbour]] tend to be more affluent, while the south is generally middle class and west is predominantly working class.]]\nThe '''economy of [[Sydney]]''' is notable for its importance in the areas of [[Trade|trading]], [[manufacturing]], [[finance]], [[education]], and [[Distribution (business)|distribution]] in [[Australia]].  Sydney has the largest economy in Australia.\n\n[[Sydney CBD|Sydney's CBD]] is the largest in Australia and also has plenty of surrounding commercial areas which are considered part of Sydney. A notable one is [[Parramatta]], which is bigger than some state capitals.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\nSydney city extends over the harbour bridge, forming [[North Sydney, New South Wales|North Sydney]], a continuation of the CBD. North Sydney has a large economy; however it tends to have a high vacancy rate. Just a few kilometres north of Sydney's city centre, is Sydney's third largest commercial area {{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}, [[Chatswood, New South Wales|Chatswood]]. Chatswood's main economy is retail and is home to many highrise buildings, with its own recognisable skyline. [[20th Century Fox]] has large Sydney studios.\n\n==History==\nAlthough the CBD dominated the city's business and cultural life in the early days, other business/cultural districts have developed in a radial pattern since [[World War II]]. In 1945, two-thirds of all jobs in Sydney were located in the [[City of Sydney]] and surrounding inner city municipalities, but post-war suburbanisation meant that only a quarter of the workforce were located in the City, [[City of South Sydney|South Sydney]], [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]] and Marrickville municipalities. \n\nWith a boom in passenger railway construction came rapid extension of the suburbs along the railway corridors to the west and south, and eventually to the North Shore, after the completion of the Harbour Bridge allowed trains to continue from [[North Sydney, New South Wales|North Sydney]] into the CBD. This radial-spoke pattern of development changed after World War II, when increasing car ownership encouraged infill development where the railways didn't run, and then further expansion around the perimeter of the city. These outer areas have mostly missed out on further rail expansion and are primarily car dependent to this day.<ref>Spearitt, Peter, 2000, ''Sydney's Century: A History'' p. 122,  Sydney: UNSW Press</ref>\n\n== Financial centre ==\n[[File:Sydney, Australia.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Sydney CBD]] is Australia's largest financial centre.]]\nSydney is a leading financial centre in the [[Asia-Pacific]] region.<ref>Daly, M. T. and Pritchard, B. 2000. Sydney:Australia's financial and commercial capital. In J. Connell (Ed.). ''Sydney the emergence of a global city.'' pp 76-95. Oxford University Press {{ISBN|0-19-550748-7}}, pp 167-188</ref> It is home to the headquarters of the [[Australian Stock Exchange]] and the [[Reserve Bank of Australia]]. It also serves as the regional headquarters for numerous multinational corporations.\n\n== Banking industry ==\nOf the 57 authorised deposit-taking banks with operations in Australia, 44 are based in Sydney\n\n== Tourism ==\n{{Main|Tourism in Sydney}}\nSydney received 8.2 million visitors in 2016, an 11.4 per cent increase from 2015. The main sources of Sydney's tourists were from north-east and south-east Asia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sydney needs more hotels, cruise ports, jobs to support tourism, academic says|first=Amanda|last=Hoh|work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]|date=20 January 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-01-20/sydney-needs-to-invest-in-tourism-says-academic/8197450}}</ref> The [[Vivid Sydney]] festival, held annually each winter, attracted 1.7 million visitors in 2015&ndash;it is the biggest festival in Australia and one of the biggest of its kind in the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vivid Festival puts Sydney in light and attracts tourism dollars|work=[[The Australian]]|first=Michaela|last=Boland|date=28 May 2016|accessdate=22 November 2017|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/vivid-festival-puts-sydney-in-lights-and-attracts-tourism-dollars/news-story/07fd2c898b56c40425a3a6a6a439c175}}</ref> The most visited landmark in the city is the [[Sydney Opera House]], located at [[Bennelong Point]], and is also the most visited landmark in Australia&ndash;the building received a $202 million renovation in 2017, known as the Renewal Project, and accommodates an average yearly audience of two million people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sydney icon's $202 million facelift gives greater access to all visitors|work=[[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]]|date=11 August 2016|accessdate=22 November 2017|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2016/08/11/sydney-icons-202-million-facelift-gives-greater-access-all-visitors}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sydney Opera House: 40 fascinating facts|work=Telegraph.co.uk|date=24 October 2013|accessdate=22 November 2017|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/oceania/australia/new-south-wales/sydney/articles/Sydney-Opera-House-40-fascinating-facts/}}</ref> Tourism in Sydney generates approximately $30 billion to the state (NSW) economy each year according to 2010 statistics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism - City of Sydney|url=http://www.cityofsydney.nsw.gov.au/business/business-support/business-in-your-sector/key-industries/tourism|accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Manufacturing ==\nSydney is the largest manufacturing hub in Australia, with the value of the city's manufacturing industry surpassing $21 billion in 2012-13, overtaking that of [[Melbourne]] ($18.9 billion)&ndash;which was formerly Australia's manufacturing heartland.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sydney takes manufacturing capital crown from Melbourne|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=8 February 2014|accessdate=4 April 2020|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/sydney-takes-manufacturing-capital-crown-from-melbourne-20140207-327c3.html}}</ref><ref>http://www.australianmanufacturing.com.au/13580/sydney-overtakes-melbourne-as-australias-biggest-manufacturing-centre</ref> Sydney's manufacturing sector consists largely of domestic-focused and high-tech manufacturing such as biotechnology, food processing and advanced electronics.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/national/sydney-takes-manufacturing-capital-crown-from-melbourne-20140207-327c3.html</ref> Major manufacturing companies with operations in Sydney include [[Arnott's Biscuits|Arnott's]], [[Coca-Cola Amatil]], [[Arrium]], Visy, [[Amcor]] and [[Rheem Manufacturing Company|Rheem]], among many others.\n\nThe ''[[Smithfield, New South Wales|Smithfield]]-[[Wetherill Park]] Industrial Estate'' in [[Greater Western Sydney]] is the largest [[industrial estate]] in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] and is the centre of manufacturing and distribution in the region. Lying between the major population growth zones in the north-west and south-west of Sydney, the estate contains more than 1,000 manufacturing, wholesale, transport and service firms which employ more than 20,000 persons.<ref>[http://www.fairfieldcity.nsw.gov.au/info/20038/snapshot_of_fairfield_city/261/smithfield-wetherill_park Smithfield-Wetherill Park]</ref><ref>[https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/south-west/dont-forget-the-southern-hemispheres-largest-industrial-zone/news-story/479f600dcc096d0325ad60fab0372f99 Don\u2019t forget the Southern Hemisphere\u2019s Largest Industrial Zone] by Marie Hogg and Simon Benson, Fairfield Advance, November 13, 2015 </ref>\n\n== Housing and employment ==\nAs of September 2003, the unemployment rate in Sydney was 5.3%.<ref name=\"2003sydney\">Australian Bureau of Statistics. 2005. [http://www.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/abs@.nsf/0/CDD66A1F353FD6A5CA256E5C00193185?Open Sydney Statistical Division]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref> As of March 2008, Sydney has the highest median house price of any Australian capital city at [[Australian dollar|$]]550,890.<ref>Australian Property Monitors. [http://www.homepriceguide.com.au/media_release/APM_HousePriceSeries_MarchQ08.pdf Official March 2008 Quarter Housing Data], Media Announcement</ref> According to ''[[The Economist]]'' Intelligence Unit's Worldwide [[cost of living]] survey, Sydney is the sixteenth most expensive city in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.eiu.com/rs/753-RIQ-438/images/WCOL_2018_Free_report.pdf?mkt_tok=eyJpIjoiWXpVd09UY3lObVF4T0RabSIsInQiOiJQUkRNc3R0SUFGcGhPNXlMY0J3OUJhZGlCZjMxTjNYS3Y5OHMwUWMxcXZacWRaR01Xd0oweGFmd1BOODB0OVNqUlB2bENBUVQxWFc3WEp4QkIwSCsyZmZJNG5SS1NscHhaMG8yZHc5NkNVZ2VGU2Zad0MzNFA1d0xneGN4ZzJTbiJ9|title=Worldwide Cost of Living 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.eiu.com/rs/753-RIQ-438/images/WCOL_2018_Free_report.pdf?mkt_tok=eyJpIjoiWXpVd09UY3lObVF4T0RabSIsInQiOiJQUkRNc3R0SUFGcGhPNXlMY0J3OUJhZGlCZjMxTjNYS3Y5OHMwUWMxcXZacWRaR01Xd0oweGFmd1BOODB0OVNqUlB2bENBUVQxWFc3WEp4QkIwSCsyZmZJNG5SS1NscHhaMG8yZHc5NkNVZ2VGU2Zad0MzNFA1d0xneGN4ZzJTbiJ9|title=Worldwide Cost of Living 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report published by the [[OECD]] in November 2005, Australia has the most overvalued houses in the Western world, with prices 52 percent higher than that justified by rental values.<ref>Boilling, M. 2 February 2006. [http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5478,18010915%5E2862,00.html City among most costly], ''Herald Sun''</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Economy of Australia]]\n*[[Economy of New South Wales]]\n*[[Sydney Chamber of Commerce]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Sydney}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economy Of Sydney}}\n[[Category:Sydney]]\n[[Category:Economy of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Economy of Sydney| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=February 2012}}\n[[File:Australian Census 2011 demographic map - Inner Sydney by POA - BCP field 0115 Median total household income weekly.svg|300px|right|thumb|Median weekly household incomes by postal area in the [[Census in Australia#2011|2011 census]], red indicates high incomes, purple indicates low incomes. The [[North Shore, Sydney|North Shore]] and areas fronting [[Sydney Harbour]] tend to be more affluent, while the south is generally middle class and west is predominantly working class.]]\nThe '''economy of [[Sydney]]''' is notable for its importance in the areas of [[Trade|trading]], [[manufacturing]], [[finance]], [[education]], and [[Distribution (business)|distribution]] in [[Australia]].  Sydney has the largest economy in Australia.\n\n[[Sydney CBD|Sydney's CBD]] is the largest in Australia and also has plenty of surrounding commercial areas which are considered part of Sydney. A notable one is [[Parramatta]], which is bigger than some state capitals.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\nSydney city extends over the harbour bridge, forming [[North Sydney, New South Wales|North Sydney]], a continuation of the CBD. North Sydney has a large economy; however it tends to have a high vacancy rate. Just a few kilometres north of Sydney's city centre, is Sydney's third largest commercial area {{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}, [[Chatswood, New South Wales|Chatswood]]. Chatswood's main economy is retail and is home to many highrise buildings, with its own recognisable skyline. [[20th Century Fox]] has large Sydney studios.\n\n==History==\nAlthough the CBD dominated the city's business and cultural life in the early days, other business/cultural districts have developed in a radial pattern since [[World War II]]. In 1945, two-thirds of all jobs in Sydney were located in the [[City of Sydney]] and surrounding inner city municipalities, but post-war suburbanisation meant that only a quarter of the workforce were located in the City, [[City of South Sydney|South Sydney]], [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]] and Marrickville municipalities. \n\nWith a boom in passenger railway construction came rapid extension of the suburbs along the railway corridors to the west and south, and eventually to the North Shore, after the completion of the Harbour Bridge allowed trains to continue from [[North Sydney, New South Wales|North Sydney]] into the CBD. This radial-spoke pattern of development changed after World War II, when increasing car ownership encouraged infill development where the railways didn't run, and then further expansion around the perimeter of the city. These outer areas have mostly missed out on further rail expansion and are primarily car dependent to this day.<ref>Spearitt, Peter, 2000, ''Sydney's Century: A History'' p. 122,  Sydney: UNSW Press</ref>\n\n== Financial centre ==\nSydney is a leading financial centre in the [[Asia-Pacific]] region.<ref>Daly, M. T. and Pritchard, B. 2000. Sydney:Australia's financial and commercial capital. In J. Connell (Ed.). ''Sydney the emergence of a global city.'' pp 76-95. Oxford University Press {{ISBN|0-19-550748-7}}, pp 167-188</ref> It is home to the headquarters of the [[Australian Stock Exchange]] and the [[Reserve Bank of Australia]]. It also serves as the regional headquarters for numerous multinational corporations.\n\n== Banking industry ==\nOf the 57 authorised deposit-taking banks with operations in Australia, 44 are based in Sydney\n\n== Tourism ==\n{{Main|Tourism in Sydney}}\nSydney received 8.2 million visitors in 2016, an 11.4 per cent increase from 2015. The main sources of Sydney's tourists were from north-east and south-east Asia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sydney needs more hotels, cruise ports, jobs to support tourism, academic says|first=Amanda|last=Hoh|work=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]|date=20 January 2017|accessdate=22 November 2017|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-01-20/sydney-needs-to-invest-in-tourism-says-academic/8197450}}</ref> The [[Vivid Sydney]] festival, held annually each winter, attracted 1.7 million visitors in 2015&ndash;it is the biggest festival in Australia and one of the biggest of its kind in the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vivid Festival puts Sydney in light and attracts tourism dollars|work=[[The Australian]]|first=Michaela|last=Boland|date=28 May 2016|accessdate=22 November 2017|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/vivid-festival-puts-sydney-in-lights-and-attracts-tourism-dollars/news-story/07fd2c898b56c40425a3a6a6a439c175}}</ref> The most visited landmark in the city is the [[Sydney Opera House]], located at [[Bennelong Point]], and is also the most visited landmark in Australia&ndash;the building received a $202 million renovation in 2017, known as the Renewal Project, and accommodates an average yearly audience of two million people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sydney icon's $202 million facelift gives greater access to all visitors|work=[[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]]|date=11 August 2016|accessdate=22 November 2017|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2016/08/11/sydney-icons-202-million-facelift-gives-greater-access-all-visitors}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sydney Opera House: 40 fascinating facts|work=Telegraph.co.uk|date=24 October 2013|accessdate=22 November 2017|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/oceania/australia/new-south-wales/sydney/articles/Sydney-Opera-House-40-fascinating-facts/}}</ref> Tourism in Sydney generates approximately $30 billion to the state (NSW) economy each year according to 2010 statistics.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism - City of Sydney|url=http://www.cityofsydney.nsw.gov.au/business/business-support/business-in-your-sector/key-industries/tourism|accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Manufacturing ==\nSydney is the largest manufacturing hub in Australia, with the value of the city's manufacturing industry surpassing $21 billion in 2012-13, overtaking that of [[Melbourne]] ($18.9 billion)&ndash;which was formerly Australia's manufacturing heartland.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sydney takes manufacturing capital crown from Melbourne|work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=8 February 2014|accessdate=4 April 2020|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/sydney-takes-manufacturing-capital-crown-from-melbourne-20140207-327c3.html}}</ref><ref>http://www.australianmanufacturing.com.au/13580/sydney-overtakes-melbourne-as-australias-biggest-manufacturing-centre</ref> Sydney's manufacturing sector consists largely of domestic-focused and high-tech manufacturing such as biotechnology, food processing and advanced electronics.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/national/sydney-takes-manufacturing-capital-crown-from-melbourne-20140207-327c3.html</ref> Major manufacturing companies with operations in Sydney include [[Arnott's Biscuits|Arnott's]], [[Coca-Cola Amatil]], [[Arrium]], Visy, [[Amcor]] and [[Rheem Manufacturing Company|Rheem]], among many others.\n\nThe ''[[Smithfield, New South Wales|Smithfield]]-[[Wetherill Park]] Industrial Estate'' in [[Greater Western Sydney]] is the largest [[industrial estate]] in the [[Southern Hemisphere]] and is the centre of manufacturing and distribution in the region. Lying between the major population growth zones in the north-west and south-west of Sydney, the estate contains more than 1,000 manufacturing, wholesale, transport and service firms which employ more than 20,000 persons.<ref>[http://www.fairfieldcity.nsw.gov.au/info/20038/snapshot_of_fairfield_city/261/smithfield-wetherill_park Smithfield-Wetherill Park]</ref><ref>[https://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/south-west/dont-forget-the-southern-hemispheres-largest-industrial-zone/news-story/479f600dcc096d0325ad60fab0372f99 Don\u2019t forget the Southern Hemisphere\u2019s Largest Industrial Zone] by Marie Hogg and Simon Benson, Fairfield Advance, November 13, 2015 </ref>\n\n== Housing and employment ==\nAs of September 2003, the unemployment rate in Sydney was 5.3%.<ref name=\"2003sydney\">Australian Bureau of Statistics. 2005. [http://www.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/abs@.nsf/0/CDD66A1F353FD6A5CA256E5C00193185?Open Sydney Statistical Division]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref> As of March 2008, Sydney has the highest median house price of any Australian capital city at [[Australian dollar|$]]550,890.<ref>Australian Property Monitors. [http://www.homepriceguide.com.au/media_release/APM_HousePriceSeries_MarchQ08.pdf Official March 2008 Quarter Housing Data], Media Announcement</ref> According to ''[[The Economist]]'' Intelligence Unit's Worldwide [[cost of living]] survey, Sydney is the sixteenth most expensive city in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.eiu.com/rs/753-RIQ-438/images/WCOL_2018_Free_report.pdf?mkt_tok=eyJpIjoiWXpVd09UY3lObVF4T0RabSIsInQiOiJQUkRNc3R0SUFGcGhPNXlMY0J3OUJhZGlCZjMxTjNYS3Y5OHMwUWMxcXZacWRaR01Xd0oweGFmd1BOODB0OVNqUlB2bENBUVQxWFc3WEp4QkIwSCsyZmZJNG5SS1NscHhaMG8yZHc5NkNVZ2VGU2Zad0MzNFA1d0xneGN4ZzJTbiJ9|title=Worldwide Cost of Living 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pages.eiu.com/rs/753-RIQ-438/images/WCOL_2018_Free_report.pdf?mkt_tok=eyJpIjoiWXpVd09UY3lObVF4T0RabSIsInQiOiJQUkRNc3R0SUFGcGhPNXlMY0J3OUJhZGlCZjMxTjNYS3Y5OHMwUWMxcXZacWRaR01Xd0oweGFmd1BOODB0OVNqUlB2bENBUVQxWFc3WEp4QkIwSCsyZmZJNG5SS1NscHhaMG8yZHc5NkNVZ2VGU2Zad0MzNFA1d0xneGN4ZzJTbiJ9|title=Worldwide Cost of Living 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report published by the [[OECD]] in November 2005, Australia has the most overvalued houses in the Western world, with prices 52 percent higher than that justified by rental values.<ref>Boilling, M. 2 February 2006. [http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5478,18010915%5E2862,00.html City among most costly], ''Herald Sun''</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Economy of Australia]]\n*[[Economy of New South Wales]]\n*[[Sydney Chamber of Commerce]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Sydney}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Economy Of Sydney}}\n[[Category:Sydney]]\n[[Category:Economy of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Economy of Sydney| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ashton 29", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinancial centre", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economy_of_Sydney"}
{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "The '''Petraio''' is a widely-known geographical and urban area in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from the upper hillside district of [[Vomero]], connecting with neighborhoods along the way, terminating in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood in downtown Naples. Mostly framed with residential buildings, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its ''basso'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself), as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.8728|N|14|14|10.7016|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nThe Petraio was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were gradually trafficked and inhabited, they were improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone paths, walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.  Its prominent sections include Gradini (steps) del Petraio, Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio, Vico (alley) del Petraio, Largo (widening) del Petraio, Rampe (ramp) del Petraio, Salita (climb) del Petraio, Via Filippo Palizzi and Via Achille Vianelli. Near one of its many prominent architectural features, Villa Santarella, the Petraio is colloquially called ''La Santarella''. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref>  the Petraio originally connected the hilltop agricultural area which the Naples downtown, the agricultural area later becoming the Vomero district &mdash; originally one of Naples most wealthy neighborhoods and today a densely populated neighborhood noted for its [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] architecture and post-war highrise apartment and condominium buildings. \n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served on Via Filippo Palizzi by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]] at Salita del Petraio and Via Filippo Palizzi.  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>  \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.8728|N|14|14|10.7016|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Petraio''' is a widely-known geographical and urban area in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from the upper hillside district of [[Vomero]], connecting with neighborhoods along the way, terminating in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood in downtown Naples. Mostly framed with residential buildings, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its ''basso'' (small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself), as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.8728|N|14|14|10.7016|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nThe Petraio was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were gradually trafficked and inhabited, they were improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone paths, walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.  Its prominent sections include Gradini (steps) del Petraio, Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio, Vico (alley) del Petraio, Largo (widening) del Petraio, Rampe (ramp) del Petraio, Salita (climb) del Petraio, Via Filippo Palizzi and Via Achille Vianelli. Near one of its many prominent architectural features, Villa Santarella, the Petraio is colloquially called ''La Santarella''. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref>  the Petraio originally connected the hilltop agricultural area which the Naples downtown, the agricultural area later becoming the Vomero district &mdash; originally one of Naples most wealthy neighborhoods and today a densely populated neighborhood noted for its [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] architecture and post-war highrise apartment and condominium buildings. \n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near its prominent [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served on Via Filippo Palizzi by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]] at Salita del Petraio and Via Filippo Palizzi.  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>  \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.8728|N|14|14|10.7016|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccess", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
